im.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gorenflos","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ewald.","German: from French <b>Gorenflos</b>, a habitational name from Gorenflos in Somme, France. <i>Gorenflo</i> is a Huguenot name, originally from Friedrichstal (founded by Huguenots), now Stutensee, near Karlsruhe (Baden-Württemberg). See also   Colliflower  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Colliflower","meanings":["Altered form of German   Gorenflo  , a surname of French origin.","History: Georg Adam Goranflo (actually <i>Gorenflo</i>) arrived in Philadelphia, PA, on the ship <i>Ann</i> in 1749 and settled in Hagerstown, MD, the name being changed to <i>Colliflower</i> in the process. His forebear Jacques de Gorenflos was a leading Huguenot in the 17th century. Religious persecution drove the family to Germany, where their surname became <i>Gorenflo</i>, and from there Georg Adam Goranflo emigrated to North America."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabeau de Gorenflos was born in 1232, in Gorenflos, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, her father, Hugues de Gorenflos, was 42 and her mother, Havoise de Drucat, was 34. She married Henri Du Boisle in 1252, in Gorenflos, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1289, in Le Boisle, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1232–1289":"1232–1289","1221–1284":"1221–1284","1253–1317":"1253–1317","1190–1254":"1190–1254","1198–1257":"1198–1257","1190":"1190","1257":"1257","1289":"1289","1232":"1232","1254":"1254","1221":"1221","1253":"1253","1198":"1198","1252":"1252","1284":"1284","1317":"1317","Le Boisle, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Le Boisle, Somme, Hauts-